\h Daniel
\toc1 Daniel
\toc2 Daniel
\toc3 Dan.
\mt1 Daniel
\mt3 (or Daniyyel)
\is1 Introduction
\ip This document is about \bk Daniel\bk* (also spelt later as вҖҳDaniyyelвҖҷ). He was captured as a young man in Yehudah (Judah) and taken to serve in Babylon. He wrote this at a time when the Jewish people were suffering a lot of mocking and persecution by those who worshipped false gods. Daniel became on of the highest officials in Babylon and we learn here about his obedience in serving God during the reigns of King Nevukadnetstsar (Nebuchadnezzar), Belshatstsar (Belshazzar), Dareyavesh (Darius), and Koresh (Cyrus). This document also has some brief but important sections telling about his three friends Hananyah, Meyshak, and Azaryah (perhaps better known as Shadrak, Meyshak, and Avednego).
\ip God's revelations which Daniel prophesied are also included here, concerning the strengthening and destruction of other nations starting with Babylon. It's also prophesied here about what would happen in the вҖҳend-timesвҖҷ.
\ip One of the themes of this document is about how God determines everything that happens in this world. He's the one who forms nations, and he's the one who determines their end. He also looks after his people.
\ip This document about Daniel was written with parts in Hebrew (1:1вҖ“2:3; 7:1вҖ“12:13) and parts in Aramaic (2:4вҖ“7:28). (Modern Syria is in the former Aram region. Aramaic is most closely related to Hebrew, Syriac, and Phoenician, and was written in a script derived from the Phoenician alphabet.)
\iot Main components of this account
\io1 God's help for Daniel and his friends \ior 1:1вҖ“6:28\ior*
\io1 God's revelations to Daniel through visions \ior 7:1вҖ“12:13\ior*
\io2 a. The four creatures \ior 7:1-28\ior*
\io2 b. The ram and the goat \ior 8:1вҖ“9:27\ior*
\io2 c. The heavenly messenger \ior 10:1вҖ“11:45\ior*
\io2 d. The time of the end \ior 12:1-13\ior*
\rem This is still a very early look into the unfinished text of the Open English Translation of the Bible. Please double-check the text in advance before using in public.
\ie
\c 1
\ms1 The account about Daniel and his friends (1:1вҖ“6:28)
\s1 Daniel and the friends his there to Babylon
\rem /s1 Daniel in Nebuchadnezzar's Court; The Young Men at Nebuchadnezzar's Court; Four Young Israelites at the Babylonian Court; Daniel's Training in Babylon; Daniel and his companions
\p
\v 1 In the third yearВҰ356354 of Yehudah'sВҰ356360 King Yehoyakim's reignВҰ356356, Babylon'sВҰ356365 King Nevukadnetstsar \add (NebuchadnezzarВҰ356362)\add* cameВҰ356361 to YerushalemВҰ356366 \add (Jerusalem)\add* andВҰ356367 besieged \add @the city\add*.\x + \xo 1:1: \xt 2Ki 24:1; 2Ch 36:5-7.\x*
\v 2 \add After two years,\add* the masterВҰ356371 \add вүҲallowed KingВҰ356376 Yehoyakim to be defeated by\add* Nevukadnetstsar who thenВҰ356370 took some of the items out of the temple andВҰ356370 took them to ShinarВҰ356387 \add (Babylonia)\add* where he placed them in his god's temple storerooms.\x + \xo 1:2-4: \xt 2Ki 20:17-18; 24:10-16; 2Ch 36:10; Isa 39:7-8.\x*
\p
\v 3 \add Some time later,\add* KingВҰ356399 \add Nevukadnetstsar\add* commanded his chiefВҰ356401 officialВҰ356402 AshpenazВҰ356400 to bringВҰ356403 him some of the young IsraeliВҰ356405 men, from both their royalВҰ356407 family andВҰ356398 from \add вүҲsome of the prominent families\add*.
\v 4 \add They had to be\add* good-looking young men without obvious defects, wise and well-educated, who would be competent for \add future\add* \add вүҲwork\add* in the palaceВҰ356435. They would be taught the language and literature of the Chaldeans,
\v 5 and king assignedВҰ356442 a daily portion of food and wine for them \add вүҲfrom his own table\add*. They would be trained for threeВҰ356457 yearsВҰ356456 \add before\add* \add вүҲentering the king'sВҰ356461 service\add*.
\v 6 Among the \add вүҲyoung men\add* from YehudahВҰ356466 \add who were chosen\add* were Daniel, HananyahВҰ356468, Misha'el, andВҰ356470 AzaryahВҰ356470,
\v 7 \add вүҲbutВҰ356472\add* \add @Ashpenaz\add* \add вүҲnamed\add* them Belteshatstsar, ShadrakВҰ356481, Meyshak, andВҰ356472 Avednego \add respectively\add*.
\p
\v 8 \add вүҲHowever\add* Daniel \add вүҲdecided\add* that he wouldn't eat the king's fancy food or drinkВҰ356500 his wine \add вүҲbecause it wasn't all вҖҳkosherвҖҷ\add*, so he requested permission from \add @Ashpenaz\add* to \add вүҲeat an alternative diet\add*.
\v 9 \add вүҲNow\add* God \add вүҲhad caused\add* the chiefВҰ356516 officialВҰ356517 to \add вүҲlike andВҰ356514 respect\add* Daniel,
\v 10 \add вүҲbutВҰ356519\add* he \add вүҲqueried\add*, вҖңI'm afraid of my masterВҰ356527 the king, who's assignedВҰ356530 your food andВҰ356519 drinkВҰ356536вҖ”\add вүҲif he saw you guys\add* lookingВҰ356543 worse than the \add вүҲothers of\add* your own age thenВҰ356519 \add вүҲI'd risk losing my headВҰ356552 if the king got angry\add*.вҖқ
\p
\v 11 \add вүҲSoВҰ356555\add* Daniel asked the steward that \add @Ashpenaz\add* had assignedВҰ356561 over \add @the four of them\add*,
\v 12 вҖңPlease test yourВҰ356576 servantsВҰ356576 for tenВҰ356578 daysВҰ356577: let us be given some vegetables to eatВҰ356585 and waterВҰ356586 to drinkВҰ356587,
\v 13 thenВҰ356589 \add after thatВҰ356598\add*, \add вүҲseeВҰ356599 how we look compared to the other young men\add* who eat the king's choice food. ThenВҰ356589 \add вүҲyouВҰ356599 can make the best decision from the evidence\add*.вҖқ
\p
\v 14 \add вүҲSoВҰ356605\add* the steward \add вүҲagreed to that\add* andВҰ356609 \add started\add* \add вүҲthe ten-day trial\add*.
\v 15 At the end of the tenВҰ356615 daysВҰ356614, they looked better andВҰ356619 healthier than all the young men who'd been eatingВҰ356626 the king'sВҰ356629 fancy food,
\v 16 \add вүҲso\add* \add after that,\add* the steward \add just\add* gave them vegetablesВҰ356641 to eat instead of the choice food andВҰ356631 wine.
\p
\v 17 \add вүҲSoВҰ356643\add* God gaveВҰ356646 those fourВҰ356645 young men knowledgeВҰ356649 and insight into all literature, and wisdomВҰ356654, and Daniel \add вүҲwas able to interpret\add* any dreamsВҰ356660 and visionsВҰ356659.
\p
\v 18 At the end of \add @the three years\add*\x + \xo 1:18 \xt 1:5\x* when the kingВҰ356667 ordered them to be brought in, the chiefВҰ356670 officialВҰ356671 \add Ashpenaz\add* brought them in to KingВҰ356667 Nevukadnetstsar.
\v 19 The king talked with \add each of\add* them and \add realised that\add* \add вүҲnone of the others were as capable as\add* Daniel, HananyahВҰ356682, Misha'el, and AzaryahВҰ356684, \add вүҲso theyВҰ356685 ended up in the king'sВҰ356687 service\add*вҖ”
\v 20 in every matterВҰ356690 of wisdomВҰ356691 and understandingВҰ356692 whichВҰ356693 the kingВҰ356697 asked them about, he foundВҰ356698 them tenВҰ356699 times better than all the magiciansВҰ356704 and astrologers \add вүҲfrom throughout\add* his entireВҰ356702 kingdomВҰ356709.
\v 21 Daniel continued \add serving\add* there through to the first yearВҰ356715 of the reign of KingВҰ356718 Koresh \add (Cyrus)\add*.
\c 2
\s1 Nevukadnetstsar's dream
\rem /s1 Daniel's wisdom; Nebuchadnezzar's Dream
\p
\v 1 \add Back in\add* the second yearВҰ356721 of King Nevukadnetstsar's reignВҰ356723, \add *the king\add* had had some dreamsВҰ356725 that troubled himвҖ”leaving him unable to sleepВҰ356730.
\v 2 \add *He\add* summoned the magiciansВҰ356737, fortune-tellers, sorcerersВҰ356739, and \add вүҲastrologers\add* to \add вүҲexplain\add* the dreamsВҰ356743 to \add *him\add*, so they came in and stoodВҰ356745 in frontВҰ356746 of the king.
\v 3 вҖңI'veВҰ356753 had a dreamВҰ356753,вҖқ the kingВҰ356751 told them, вҖңandВҰ356754 my spirit is \add вүҲanxious to understand\add* \add *it\add*.вҖқ
\v 4 The \add вүҲastrologers\add* spokeВҰ356761 to the king in AramaicВҰ356764, вҖңLong live KingВҰ356763 Nevukadnetstsar. Tell us what you dreamtВҰ356769, andВҰ356761 thenВҰ356761 we'll give you the interpretationВҰ356772.вҖқ
\p
\v 5 вҖң\add вүҲI've already made my decision\add*,вҖқ the kingВҰ356776 replied. вҖңIf you all can'tВҰ356784 tell me the dreamВҰ356786 and \add then give\add* itsВҰ356787 interpretationВҰ356787, you'll all be torn limb from limb and yourВҰ356790 housesВҰ356790 made into a rubbish heap.
\v 6 ButВҰ356794 if you all explain the dream and its interpretation, you'll receiveВҰ356802 giftsВҰ356798 from me, and a rewardВҰ356799 and greatВҰ356801 honour. SoВҰ356794 tell me the dream and its interpretation.вҖқ
\p
\v 7 вҖңLetВҰ356814 the kingВҰ356814 tell his servantsВҰ356817 the dreamВҰ356815,вҖқ theyВҰ356813 \add вүҲinsisted\add*, вҖңand we'll give the interpretationВҰ356818.вҖқ
\p
\v 8 вҖңI know for certainВҰ356826 that you're all trying to gain timeВҰ356830,вҖқ the kingВҰ356822 answered. вҖң\add вүҲHowever, I've made up my mind\add*
\v 9 that if you all don'tВҰ356847 \add вүҲtell me what my dream was\add*, \add вүҲthen yourВҰ356852 fate is already clear\add* because you've \add obviously\add* agreedВҰ356856 togetherВҰ356856 to \add вүҲkeep feeding me with lies and made-up stories untilВҰ356861 I give in\add*. So then, tell me what \add &my\add* dream was, and then I'llВҰ356869 \add вүҲbe confident\add* that you can give me its interpretationВҰ356871.вҖқ
\p
\v 10 вҖңThere's no one \add вүҲin the whole world who could tell\add* the king that,вҖқ the \add вүҲastrologers\add* answered the king. вҖңNo greatВҰ356900 and powerfulВҰ356901 king has askedВҰ356905 any magicianВҰ356908 or enchanter or \add вүҲastrologer\add* to do that \add beforeВҰ356877\add*!
\v 11 WhatВҰ356924 you're requesting, \add вүҲyour majesty\add*, is difficultВҰ356917, andВҰ356918 \add вүҲno human can tell you\add* \add what you dreamt\add*вҖ”only the godsВҰ356926.вҖқ
\v 12 \add вүҲThat angered the kingВҰ356939, and he got so furiousВҰ356941 that he ordered for all the Babylonian wise menВҰ356946 to be executed\add*.
\p
\v 13 \add вүҲWhenВҰ356949\add* the decreeВҰ356949 wentВҰ356950 out that \add all\add* the wise menВҰ356951 were to \add be rounded up to\add* be executedВҰ356956, DanielВҰ356954 andВҰ356949 his friendsВҰ356955 \add were included\add*.
\rem /s1 God Shows Daniel What the Dream Means
\v 14 AryokВҰ356964 was the captain of the king's guards who'd been sentВҰ356961 to executeВҰ356967 the Babylonian wise men, \add butВҰ356963\add* Daniel spoke to him with \add вүҲwise andВҰ356963 prudent\add* \add caution\add*.
\p
\v 15 He asked the king's commander Aryok, вҖңWhy \add вүҲdid the king come to that sudden decision\add*?вҖқ Aryok \add вүҲexplained what had happened\add*,
\v 16 \add вүҲsoВҰ356998\add* DanielВҰ357003 went to the king andВҰ356998 requested some time so he would be able to give the interpretationВҰ357009 to \add *him\add*.
\p
\rem /s1 God Reveals Nebuchadnezzar's Dream
\v 17 Then Daniel wentВҰ357017 \add back\add* to his houseВҰ357016 and told his companions HananyahВҰ357018, Misha'el, and AzaryahВҰ357020
\v 18 \add вүҲso\add* theyВҰ357038 \add вүҲmight beg\add* for mercy from the godВҰ357030 of the heavensВҰ357031 concerningВҰ357032 the mysteryВҰ357034 \add of the dream\add*, so that \add вүҲall of them\add* might not be executed along with the rest of the Babylonian wise menВҰ357044.
\v 19 Then the mysteryВҰ357053 was revealedВҰ357054 to Daniel in a visionВҰ357049 during the nightВҰ357052. Aftewrwards, Daniel blessedВҰ357057 the godВҰ357058 of the heavensВҰ357059
\v 20 sayingВҰ357063, вҖңLet God's nameВҰ357065 be blessedВҰ357069 forever and ever, because \add all\add* wisdomВҰ357077 and powerВҰ357078 belong to him.
\v 21 He moves the timesВҰ357086 and seasonsВҰ357087 forwards. He removesВҰ357088 \add some\add* kings and \add вүҲgives power to others\add*. It's him who gives wisdomВҰ357093 to the wise and knowledgeВҰ357095 to those who have understanding.
\v 22 He revealsВҰ357100 the deep and hiddenВҰ357102 thingsВҰ357101вҖ”he knows what is in the darknessВҰ357105, and the lightВҰ357106 lives with him.
\v 23 Oh GodВҰ357113 of my ancestorsВҰ357114, I thank you and praise you for the wisdomВҰ357119 and powerВҰ357120 you have givenВҰ357121 to me. Now you've revealed to me what we askedВҰ357127 you about because you've told us what the kingВҰ357132 is wanting to know.вҖқ
\s1 Daniel explains the king's dream
\rem /s1 Daniel Tells the King the Dream and Explains It; Daniel Interprets the Dream
\p
\v 24 So Daniel went to AryokВҰ357143, the man that the king had appointedВҰ357145 to execute Babylon'sВҰ357149 wise men, and told him, вҖңDon't hurt the wise men in Babylon. Take me in to the king and I'llВҰ357166 tell \add *him\add* the \add dream and its\add* interpretationВҰ357164.вҖқ
\p
\v 25 AryokВҰ357170 quickly took Daniel in to the king and told him, вҖңI'veВҰ357182 foundВҰ357182 a man among the exilesВҰ357187 from YehudahВҰ357189 who will reveal the interpretationВҰ357191 \add of your dream\add*.вҖқ
\p
\v 26 вҖңAre you able to tell me the dreamВҰ357206 thatВҰ357207 I sawВҰ357209, and its interpretationВҰ357210?вҖқ the kingВҰ357196 \add вүҲasked\add* Daniel (also called Belteshatstsar).
\p
\v 27 вҖңNo wise men, enchanters, magiciansВҰ357225, or astrologersВҰ357226 are able to do what the king has demanded,вҖқ replied Daniel.
\v 28 вҖңHowever, thereВҰ357232 is a godВҰ357233 in the heavensВҰ357234 who revealsВҰ357235 mysteries, and he's the one who's shown you, KingВҰ357238 Nevukadnetstsar, what will happen in the daysВҰ357244 \add вүҲto come\add*. This was your dreamВҰ357245 and the visionsВҰ357246 in your mind while you were in your bed:
\v 29 OhВҰ357258 kingВҰ357258, \add вүҲas you lay there\add* your thoughtsВҰ357259 turned to what would happen \add вүҲin the future\add*, and the one who revealsВҰ357269 mysteriesВҰ357270 showed you what is going to happen.
\v 30 As for me, this mysteryВҰ357289 was revealed to me, not because I'm wiser than \add вүҲanyone else\add*, butВҰ357277 so that the interpretationВҰ357298 could be revealed to the kingВҰ357299, andВҰ357277 so that you can \add вүҲunderstand what you saw inВҰ357279\add* your mindВҰ357302.
\p
\v 31 вҖңWhat you were looking at, \add вүҲyourВҰ357321 majesty\add*, was an incredible, hugeВҰ357314 statueВҰ357315. It was heavy and \add вүҲshone brightly\add* as it stood \add there\add* \add вүҲin frontВҰ357321 of\add* youвҖ”a terrifyingВҰ357323 sight.
\v 32 The statue'sВҰ357326 headВҰ357327 was made of pure goldВҰ357330, its chestВҰ357332 and arms were silverВҰ357335, its bellyВҰ357336 and thighsВҰ357337 were bronzeВҰ357339,
\v 33 its legs were made of iron, and its feetВҰ357344 were \add вүҲa combination\add* of iron and clay.
\v 34 You continued looking untilВҰ357356 a stoneВҰ357359 was \add вүҲsupernaturally\add* cut out \add from a mountain\add*, and it \add tumbled down and\add* struckВҰ357364 the statueВҰ357365 onВҰ357363 its feetВҰ357368 of iron and clay, and it smashed them to pieces.
\v 35 Then the iron, the clay, the bronzeВҰ357380, the silverВҰ357381, and the goldВҰ357382 were crushed all at the same time and became like the \add вүҲsmall pieces of dry straw at harvest time in\add* the summerВҰ357389. Then the windВҰ357392 carriedВҰ357390 them away so that no trace of them could be foundВҰ357398, \add вүҲbutВҰ357382\add* the stoneВҰ357400 that struckВҰ357404 the statueВҰ357405 became a hugeВҰ357408 mountainВҰ357407 that then filledВҰ357409 the whole world.
\p
\v 36 вҖңThatВҰ357420 was the dreamВҰ357415, andВҰ357416 \add now\add* we'll tell the kingВҰ357420 itsВҰ357416 meaning:
\v 37 YouВҰ357425, \add вүҲyour majesty\add*, are the king of kingsВҰ357427 who has been givenВҰ357435 the kingdomВҰ357431, the powerВҰ357432, the strengthВҰ357433, and the splendour by the godВҰ357429 of the heavensВҰ357430.
\v 38 Wherever people live, he's \add вүҲplaced you in charge of\add* them, \add and\add* he's \add even\add* put you over the animalsВҰ357447 in the countrysideВҰ357448 and the birds in the skiesВҰ357451, \add so\add* you'reВҰ357456 the \add statue's\add* goldВҰ357463 headВҰ357461.
\v 39 \add вүҲButВҰ357465 another less prominent kingdom will follow yours\add*, thenВҰ357465 another kingdom of bronzeВҰ357479 to rule over all the earthВҰ357484 \add afterВҰ357465 thatВҰ357480\add*.
\v 40 ThenВҰ357486 there'll be a fourthВҰ357487 kingdomВҰ357486 that's strongВҰ357490 as ironвҖ”becauseВҰ357494 iron crushesВҰ357503 andВҰ357486 shattersВҰ357497 all things. Like an iron \add sledge-hammer\add* that smashes things into pieces, it will smash all those others into \add вүҲbroken\add* pieces.
\v 41 And as you saw the feetВҰ357513 and toes, \add вүҲa mixture of iron and potter'sВҰ357521 clay\add*, it will be a dividedВҰ357526 kingdomВҰ357525вҖ”some of the iron's strengthВҰ357530 will be inВҰ357535 it, just as you saw iron mixedВҰ357542 withВҰ357535 the soft clay.
\v 42 As the feetВҰ357547 were partly iron and partly clay, so that kingdomВҰ357557 will be partly strongВҰ357559 and partly \add вүҲweak\add*.
\v 43 As youВҰ357566 sawВҰ357566 the iron mixedВҰ357568 with soft clay, so \add вүҲvarious peoples will make alliances with each other\add*, butВҰ357575 they won'tВҰ357575 \add вүҲstick together\add* just as iron doesn't \add вүҲintegrate\add* with clay.
\v 44 In the daysВҰ357593 of those kingsВҰ357595, the godВҰ357598 of the heavensВҰ357599 will establish a kingdom thatВҰ357601 will never be destroyedВҰ357604 or \add вүҲtaken over by others\add*. It will crush all those kingdomsВҰ357615 andВҰ357593 put an end to them, \add вүҲbutВҰ357593\add* it will stand foreverВҰ357618.
\v 45 Just as you sawВҰ357625 that a stoneВҰ357629 was \add вүҲsupernaturally\add* cut out of the mountainВҰ357627, and that it crushedВҰ357634 the iron, the bronzeВҰ357636, the clay, the silverВҰ357638, and the goldВҰ357639, the \add вүҲpowerful\add* GodВҰ357640 has revealed to the kingВҰ357643 what will happen \add вүҲinВҰ357633 the future\add*. The dreamВҰ357650 is true, and its interpretationВҰ357652 is trustworthyВҰ357651.вҖқ
\s1 Daniel is rewarded by the king
\rem /s1 Daniel and His Friends Promoted; The King Rewards Daniel; Nebuchadnezzar Rewards Daniel
\p
\v 46 Then KingВҰ357656 Nevukadnetstsar fell \add вүҲto his knees with his faceВҰ357661 to the ground to worship\add* Daniel, and he commanded that a \add burnt\add* offering and incenseВҰ357665 be offered up to him.
\v 47 The king said to Daniel, вҖңIt's true that your godВҰ357678 is the god of godsВҰ357681 and the master of masters, and the one who reveals mysteries, because you'veВҰ357687 been able to reveal this mystery.вҖқ
\v 48 Then the kingВҰ357693 gave Daniel high honours and gave him many great giftsВҰ357696, and he made him rulerВҰ357702 over the whole provinceВҰ357706 of Babylon and chiefВҰ357708 supervisor over all of Babylon'sВҰ357707 wise menВҰ357714.
\v 49 Daniel \add вүҲaskedВҰ357718 the king to appointВҰ357722\add* ShadrakВҰ357728 \add (Hananyah)\add*, Meyshak \add (Misha'el)\add*, andВҰ357717 Avednego \add (Azaryah)\add* over the administrationВҰ357724 of the Babylonian provinceВҰ357726, \add вүҲbutВҰ357717\add* Daniel remained atВҰ357733 the king's courtВҰ357733.
\c 3
\s1 The command to worship the statue
\rem /s1 Nebuchadnezzar Commands Everyone to Worship a Gold Statue; The fiery furnace; Nebuchadnezzar's Gold Statue; The Image of Gold and the Fiery Furnace; The Golden Image
\p
\v 1 KingВҰ357738 Nevukadnetstsar \add (NebuchadnezzarВҰ357737)\add* had a goldВҰ357743 statue made that stood nearly thirty metres high and was almost three metres wide, and itВҰ357750 was erected onВҰ357751 the Dura plainВҰ357751 inВҰ357751 the Babylonian provinceВҰ357753.
\v 2 ThenВҰ357756 KingВҰ357757 Nevukadnetstsar sentВҰ357758 for the \add вүҲvarious levels of\add* governorsВҰ357763, the counsellorsВҰ357764, the treasurersВҰ357765, the judgesВҰ357766, the magistratesВҰ357767, andВҰ357756 all the provincialВҰ357770 officials, to all comeВҰ357771 to the dedicationВҰ357772 of the statueВҰ357773 thatВҰ357774 \add *he'd\add* erected.
\v 3 \add вүҲSo all those officials assembled in front of the statue thatВҰ357793 the kingВҰ357796 had set up, ready\add* for the dedicationВҰ357791.
\v 4 ThenВҰ357805 the heraldВҰ357805 loudly proclaimedВҰ357806, вҖңYouВҰ357810 peoplesВҰ357810, nationsВҰ357811, andВҰ357812 languagesВҰ357812 are commanded
\v 5 that any timeВҰ357814 you hearВҰ357817 the soundВҰ357818 of the horn, fluteВҰ357820, lyre, harps, pipes, and \add вүҲother instruments\add*, you all must bow down and worshipВҰ357830 the goldВҰ357832 statueВҰ357831 that KingВҰ357836 NevukadnetstsarВҰ357835 has erected.
\v 6 \add вүҲAnyone who refuses\add* to bow down andВҰ357844 worshipВҰ357844 \add >it\add* atВҰ357845 that time, will be thrownВҰ357848 into a blazingВҰ357853 furnaceВҰ357851.вҖқ
\v 7 \add вүҲSo when all those people who had gathered heard the soundsВҰ357867 made by the musicalВҰ357876 instruments\add*, theyВҰ357883 all bowed down to worship the goldВҰ357885 statueВҰ357884.
\s1 Daniel's three friends get tattled on
\rem /s1 Daniel's Three Friends Are Accused of Disobedience
\p
\v 8 \add вүҲButВҰ357901\add* some ChaldeanВҰ357900 \add astrologers\add* \add вүҲwent to the king to make trouble for\add* the JewsВҰ357904.
\v 9 They reported to KingВҰ357909 Nevukadnetstsar, вҖңLong live the king.
\v 10 OhВҰ357916 kingВҰ357916, you've made a decreeВҰ357918 that everyВҰ357920 man who hears the soundВҰ357926 of the \add вүҲmusicalВҰ357937 instruments\add*, must bow down and worshipВҰ357939 the goldВҰ357941 statueВҰ357940,
\v 11 \add вүҲbutВҰ357943\add* anyone who doesn't bow andВҰ357949 worshipВҰ357949 will be thrownВҰ357950 into a fiery furnaceВҰ357953.
\v 12 \add Now,\add* there are certain Jews who you've appointedВҰ357962 over the administrationВҰ357966 of the provinceВҰ357967 of BabylonВҰ357968: ShadrakВҰ357969, Meyshak, and Avednego. These men, \add вүҲyour majesty\add*, \add вүҲdon't take any notice of\add* you: they don't serve your godsВҰ357982, or worship the goldВҰ357987 statueВҰ357986 thatВҰ357988 you've set up.вҖқ
\p
\v 13 Then Nevukadnetstsar inВҰ357996 a furiousВҰ357997 rageВҰ357996 commanded that ShadrakВҰ358000 \add (Hananyah)\add*, Meyshak \add (Misha'el)\add*, and Avednego \add (Azaryah)\add* be \add вүҲarrested\add*. Then \add *they\add* were broughtВҰ358007 to the kingВҰ358009
\v 14 \add вүҲwho questioned\add* them, вҖңShadrakВҰ358016, Meyshak, and Avednego, is it true that you won'tВҰ358021 serve my godsВҰ358020 or worship the goldВҰ358025 statueВҰ358024 that I set up?
\v 15 Now if you're readyВҰ358034, as soon as you hearВҰ358039 the \add вүҲmusical instruments\add* of music, if you all bow down and worshipВҰ358054 the statueВҰ358055 I \add вүҲerected\add*, \add вүҲeverything will be okay\add*. ButВҰ358048 if you don'tВҰ358060, you'll immediately be thrownВҰ358065 into a blazingВҰ358070 hot furnaceВҰ358068. \add вүҲThen what godВҰ358074 could rescueВҰ358077 you from my punishment\add*?вҖқ
\p
\v 16 вҖңOh Nevukadnetstsar,вҖқ \add *the three of them\add* answered the kingВҰ358088, вҖңweВҰ358093 don'tВҰ358090 need to answer \add that last question\add*.
\v 17 \add вүҲIf that's what happens to us\add*, the godВҰ358102 that weВҰ358105 serve is able to rescue us from the blazingВҰ358113 fireВҰ358112 \add вүҲand from yourВҰ358116 punishment. He will save us,\add* \add вүҲyour majesty\add*.
\v 18 \add вүҲButВҰ358126 just so it's clear\add* \add вүҲyour majesty\add*, even if he doesn't, we won'tВҰ358121 serve your godsВҰ358128 or worship thatВҰ358138 goldВҰ358137 statueВҰ358136.вҖқ
\s1 Shadrak, Meyshak, and Avednego thrown into the fire
\rem /s1 The Fiery Furnace; Daniel's Three Friends Are Sentenced to Death; The Blazing Furnace
\p
\v 19 \add вүҲThat made Nevukadnetstsar absolutely furious and it could be seen in his faceВҰ358149\add*. He ordered that the furnaceВҰ358161 be made sevenВҰ358164 times hotter \add вүҲthan usual\add*
\v 20 and commanded \add вүҲsome of his top warriorsВҰ358170\add* to tie up ShadrakВҰ358178, Meyshak, and Avednego and thenВҰ358170 to throwВҰ358182 them into the blazingВҰ358185 furnaceВҰ358183.
\v 21 \add вүҲSo while still fully dressed even withВҰ358191 their turbansВҰ358195 still onВҰ358191,\add* theyВҰ358190 were tied up and thrownВҰ358197 into the middle of the furnaceВҰ358200 where the fireВҰ358201 was blazingВҰ358202.
\v 22 \add Unfortunately\add*, becauseВҰ358206 of the king's insistent command, the furnaceВҰ358214 was extremely hot and the flamesВҰ358227 killedВҰ358225 the menВҰ358217 who \add вүҲthrew them in\add*,
\v 23 \add вүҲbutВҰ358231\add* ShadrakВҰ358234, Meyshak, andВҰ358236 Avednego fell into the \add вүҲroaring flames while still securely tied up\add*.
\p
\v 24 Then KingВҰ358250 Nevukadnetstsar was startled and jumped up and asked his counsellorsВҰ358256, вҖңWasn't it threeВҰ358259 \add вүҲwho were tied up\add* that were thrownВҰ358260 \add there\add* into the middle of the fireВҰ358263?
\p вҖңCertainly, \add вүҲyour majesty\add*,вҖқ they replied.
\p
\v 25 вҖңLook \add thereВҰ358287, then\add*!вҖқ he responded. вҖңI can see \em fourВҰ358278\em* menВҰ358277 walkingВҰ358280 inВҰ358281 the middle of the fireВҰ358283, and they're not tied up and they're not hurt, and the fourthВҰ358291 one looks like a \add вүҲyoung god\add*.вҖқ
\rem /s1 The Three Men Are Released and Promoted
\p
\v 26 Then Nevukadnetstsar went over by the furnaceВҰ358303 doorВҰ358302 and \add вүҲcalled out\add*, вҖңShadrak, Meyshak, and Avednego, servantsВҰ358313 of the Most High GodВҰ358316, come out, and come over here!вҖқ Then \add *the three men\add* walked out from the middle of the fire.
\v 27 \add вүҲAll the king's officials\add* gatheredВҰ358332 \add вүҲaroundВҰ358332 them\add* and saw that the fire \add вүҲhadn't harmed them\add*вҖ”their hair wasn't even singedВҰ358350, their cloaks weren't damaged, and \add вүҲthey didn'tВҰ358342 even smellВҰ358354 like smoke\add*.
\p
\v 28 Nevukadnetstsar \add вүҲspoke\add*, вҖң\add вүҲPraise\add* the god of ShadrakВҰ358367, Meyshak, and Avednego. He sent his angel and rescuedВҰ358375 his servantsВҰ358376 who \add вүҲhad put their trustВҰ358378\add* in him. They \add вүҲtook objection to\add* the king's commandВҰ358380 \add вүҲat the cost of their own lives\add*, rather than serve or worship any god exceptВҰ358397 their god.
\v 29 I \add вүҲhereby\add* make a decreeВҰ358402 that any people, nationВҰ358407, or languageВҰ358408 that speaks anything offensive againstВҰ358414 the godВҰ358415 of ShadrakВҰ358418, Meyshak, and Avednego will have theirВҰ358415 housesВҰ358424 made into \add #rubbish heaps\add* and they'll \add вүҲbe torn limb from limb\add*, becauseВҰ358429 there'sВҰ358432 no other god who's able to save \add people\add* like that.вҖқ
\p
\v 30 Then the kingВҰ358442 \add вүҲgave\add* ShadrakВҰ358444 \add (Hananyah)\add*, Meyshak \add (Misha'el)\add*, andВҰ358446 Avednego \add (Azaryah)\add* \add вүҲmore important positions inВҰ358448 BabylonВҰ358449 provinceВҰ358448 than they had before\add*.
\c 4
\s1 The second dream of King Nevukadnetstsar
\rem /s1 Nebuchadnezzar's Dream of a Tree; Nebuchadnezzar's Second Dream; Nebuchadnezzar's madness; Nebuchadnezzar's Dream about a Tree
\p
\v 1 King Nevukadnetstsar \add (NebuchadnezzarВҰ358501)\add* \add sent this message\add* to all people groups, nations, and languages that live all over the world:
\p May you \add вүҲhave peace and prosperityВҰ358505\add*.
\v 2 It seemed good to me to \add вүҲlet you all know about\add* the \add вүҲamazing miracles\add* that the \add вүҲsupreme\add* God has done for me.
\q1
\v 3 The miracles he does are incredible,
\q1 вүҲand his acts of creation are powerful.
\q1 His kingdom will last forever,
\q1 вүҲand his authority goes from one generation to another.
\p
\v 4 I, Nevukadnetstsar, was \add вүҲdoing well at home\add*, and prospering \add at my work\add* in my palace,
\v 5 \add вүҲbutВҰ358555\add* \add one night\add* as I lay in bed, I had a dreamВҰ358572 that scared meвҖ”the images and visions in my head terrified me.
\v 6 \add вүҲSo I summoned\add* all of Babylon's wise men to come and tell me the interpretationВҰ358601 of the dreamВҰ358597.
\v 7 \add вүҲWhen\add* those magicians, fortune-tellers, sorcerers and astrologers arrived, I told them the dream, butВҰ358605 they didn't know the interpretation.
\p
\v 8 Finally, Daniel came inвҖ”he'd been named Belteshatstsar \add (Belteshazzar)\add* after my god's name. The spirit of the holy gods is in him, and I told him the dream:
\v 9 вҖңOh Belteshatstsar, chief of the magicians, since I know that the spirit of the holy gods is inВҰ358640 you and that no mystery is too difficult for you, \add вүҲgo through\add* the visions of my dream and tell me their interpretation.
\p
\v 10 This is the visionВҰ358660 that was in my mind as a lay in bed: I was looking and was surprised to seeВҰ358665 \add вүҲa very tall\add* tree growing in the middle of \add вүҲa field\add*.
\v 11 The treeВҰ358679 kept growing taller and stronger \add вүҲuntil\add* its top reached the sky and it \add вүҲcould be seen from all over the world\add*.
\v 12 It had beautiful leavesВҰ358701 were beautiful and lots of fruit onВҰ358700 it. It \add provided\add* food for everything, the animalsВҰ358715 in the countrysideВҰ358709 found shade under it, and the birds of the sky lived in its branches. \add вүҲEvery living thing benefitted\add* from it.
\p
\v 13 I was looking at the visions in my mindВҰ358721 as I lay in bed, and then, wow, a holy sentinel came down from the heavens.
\v 14 He shouted loudly, вҖҳChop that tree down and cut its branches off, strip off its leaves, and scatter its fruit. Let the animals \add вүҲrun away\add* from under it and the birds from its branches.
\v 15 ButВҰ358776 leave the stump with its roots in the ground, and bind it with a band of iron and bronze. Let it become wet with the dew in the tender grass of the field, \add вүҲaccompanied only by those animals that live\add* in the grass.
\v 16 Let his mind\f + \fr 4:16 \ft It seems now that the tree represented a man.\f* be changed from a man to an animal as seven periods pass over himВҰ358817.
\v 17 \add &That\add* sentence is by the decree of the sentinels, and the decision is a command of the holy ones, so that the living may know that the highest one is ruler over human \add #kingdoms\add* and gives \add #them\add* to whoever he wantsвҖ”even to those \add вүҲwho seem unimportant\add*.вҖҷ
\p
\v 18 I, King Nevukadnetstsar, had this dream. Now you, O Belteshatstsar, tell me the interpretation, because none of the wise men in my kingdom can tell me the interpretation. ButВҰ358855 you can, because the spirit of the holy gods is in you.вҖқ
\s1 The saving/explaining of Daniel of dream of King
\rem /s1 Daniel Explains the Dream; Daniel Interprets the Second Dream; Daniel Interprets the Dream
\p
\v 19 Daniel (also known as Belteshatstsar) was appalled for a while \add at the meaning of the dream\add*, and \add вүҲworried how to present it\add*. The kingВҰ358877 \add saw this\add* and said, Belteshatstsar, don't \add вүҲhold back on being honest about\add* the dream its interpretation.вҖқ
\p вҖңMy master,вҖқ \add *he\add* answered, вҖң\add вүҲIf only\add* the dream was for those who hate you, and its interpretation was for your enemies.
\v 20 YouВҰ358892 sawВҰ358891 that treeВҰ358902 that grew and became strong, and whose top reached the sky and was visible all \add вүҲover the world\add*,
\v 21 with its beautiful leaves and plentiful fruit. \add вүҲIt provided\add* food for everyone, and the animals from the countryside lived under it, and the birds lived in its branches.
\v 22 That was you, \add вүҲyour majesty\add*. You've grown and become strongвҖ”your greatness has grown and reaches to heavenВҰ358967, and your dominion to the ends of the earth.
\v 23 \add вүҲThen\add* the king saw a holy sentinel coming down from heavenВҰ359011 and saying, вҖҳChop down the treeВҰ359001 and destroy it, butВҰ358995 leaveВҰ358997 the stumpВҰ358998 and the rootsВҰ358999 in the ground, bound with a band of iron and bronze, in the tender grass of the countryside, and let him be wet with the dew, and let \add вүҲhim live\add* with the animals of the fields until seven periods of time pass over him.вҖҷ
\p
\v 24 вҖң\add вүҲYour majesty\add*, this is the interpretation: It's \add actually\add* the decree of what the supreme God has declared will happen to \add youВҰ359018\add*, my master the kingВҰ359015.
\v 25 You will be driven \add вүҲaway from society\add* and you'll live with the animals in the countryside. You'll be forced to eat grass like a bull, and you'll \add sleep on the ground and\add* be wet with dew \add in the morning\add* for seven \add вүҲyears\add* until you acknowledge that the highest one is ruler over \add вүҲhumankind\add* and \add вүЎlearn that\add* he gives kingdoms to whoever he wants.
\v 26 \add вүҲButВҰ359052\add* \add just\add* as it was commanded to leave the stump of the tree with its roots, \add so too\add* your kingdomВҰ359050 will be restored to you from the time you recognise that heaven rules \add over earth\add*.
\v 27 Therefore, \add вүҲyour majestyВҰ359075\add*, \add вүҲplease consider\add* my advice: \add вүҲstop sinning and do what is right\add*, and \add вүЎstop\add* \add вүҲdisobeying God by starting to\add* show mercy to the oppressed, so thatВҰ359066 perhaps your prosperity \add вүҲmightВҰ359072 be prolonged\add*.вҖқ
\rem /s1 The Dream's Fulfillment; Nebuchadnezzar's Humiliation; The Dream Is Fulfilled
\p
\v 28 \add But\add* all of that did happen to KingВҰ359081 Nevukadnetstsar.
\v 29 Twelve months \add вүҲlater,\add* he was walking onВҰ359125 \add the upper terrace of\add* the royal palace inВҰ359125 Babylon
\v 30 \add вүҲwhen\add* \add *he\add* \add looked across\add* and said, вҖңIsn't that the great Babylon, which I've built as a royal residence by the strength of my power and for the glory of my majesty?вҖқ
\p
\v 31 \add вүҲHe'd only just finished saying that when he heard a voice in\add* the sky, вҖңIt's \add now\add* decreed to you, King NebuchadnezzarВҰ359165: you've just lost your kingdomВҰ359184.
\v 32 You'll be driven away from \add other\add* people, and \add вүҲyou'll live\add* will be withВҰ359200 the animals \add out\add* inВҰ359200 the countryside \add where\add* you'll \add вүҲhave to\add* eat grass like a cow. Seven \add вүҲyears will pass before\add* you acknowledge that the highest one is ruler over mankind and he gives \add @kingdoms\add* to whoever he wants.вҖқ
\p
\v 33 Immediately \add вүҲwhat had been said inВҰ359217 advance happened to\add* Nebuchadnezzar. He was driven away from \add вүҲsociety\add*. He ate grass like a cow, and his body was wet withВҰ359217 dew \add each morning after sleeping onВҰ359217 the ground\add*. \add вүҲEventually\add* his hair had grown long like eagles' feathers, and his nails \add вүЎwere long\add* like birds' claws.
\s1 Nevukadnetstsar praises God
\rem /s1 Nebuchadnezzar Praises God
\p
\v 34 вҖңAfter \add the seven years\add*, I, Nevukadnetstsar \add вүҲlooked up toward\add* heavenВҰ359251 and my reason returned to me. Then I praisedВҰ359247 and honouredВҰ359249 the highest one who lives forever, because his authority is everlasting and his kingdom endures \add вүҲthrough the generations\add*.
\v 35 \add Compared to him,\add* all the inhabitants of the earth are \add вүҲinsignificant like ants\add*вҖ”he \add вүҲissues his commands\add* to the heavenly army and to earth's inhabitants. No one can hold back his hand or \add вүҲhas any right to ask\add* him, вҖҳWhat have you done?вҖҷ вҖқ
\p
\v 36 вҖңAt that time my sanity returned to me, and I was reestablished in my kingdom. My majesty and my splendour was restored to me \add вүҲas I became again the respected leader\add* of my kingdom. My counsellors and my nobles \add вүҲwanted to be in my company\add*, and \add вүҲI became even more powerful than I was before\add*.
\v 37 Now I, Nevukadnetstsar, praise, extol, and honour the king of the heavens, because \add вүҲeverything he does is\add*, and his \add вүҲmethods\add* are just, and he's able to humble those who \add вүҲbecome proud\add*.
\c 5
\s1 The writing on the wall
\rem /s1 Belshazzar's Banquet; The writing on the wall; Belshazzar's Feast; The Writing on the Wall
\p
\v 1 \add Several years later when\add* Belshatstsar \add was\add* king, he put on a feastВҰ359269 for a thousand of his noblesВҰ359271, and he was drinkingВҰ359276 wine with them \add *all\add*.
\v 2 \add вүҲAs Belshatstsar was drinking\add* the wine, he \add remembered\add* the goldВҰ359285 and silverВҰ359286 cups that his fatherВҰ359290 Nevukadnetstsar had taken from the templeВҰ359293 in YerushalemВҰ359295, \add and\add* ordered that they be broughtВҰ359288 in so that the kingВҰ359298 and his noblesВҰ359299, and his wivesВҰ359300 and his concubinesВҰ359301, could drinkВҰ359296 from them.
\v 3 \add вүҲSo\add* they brought in the goldВҰ359306 cups thatВҰ359307 had been taken out of God's residence in YerushalemВҰ359317, then the kingВҰ359320 and his noblesВҰ359321, his wivesВҰ359322 and his concubinesВҰ359323, drankВҰ359318 from them.
\v 4 They drankВҰ359325 the wine and praisedВҰ359327 the godsВҰ359328 of goldВҰ359329 and silverВҰ359330, bronzeВҰ359331, iron, wood, and stoneВҰ359334.
\rem /s1 The Writing on the Wall
\p
\v 5 Suddenly, the fingersВҰ359341 of a humanВҰ359345 hand appeared and started writing on the plasterВҰ359351 on the king's palaceВҰ359355 wall, opposite the lampstandВҰ359348. \add When\add* the king saw the back of the hand thatВҰ359362 was writing,
\v 6 he \add вүҲwas very frightened and the colour drained from his faceВҰ359367\add*. HisВҰ359366 \add вүҲlegs felt weak\add* and his kneesВҰ359375 started knockingВҰ359378 \add together\add*,
\v 7 \add and\add* \add *he\add* called out for the enchantersВҰ359384, the Chaldeans, and the astrologersВҰ359387 to be brought in. The king told those Babylonian wise men, вҖңAnyone who can read this writingВҰ359401 and tell me its interpretationВҰ359403 will be \add вүҲdressed in royal robes\add* and will have a chainВҰ359407 of goldВҰ359412 \add placed\add* around his neck, and he'll become the thirdВҰ359416 ruler in the kingdomВҰ359417.вҖқ
\v 8 \add вүҲWhenВҰ359426\add* all the king's wise men of the king \add вүҲgot there\add*, \add вүҲnone of them\add* could read the writingВҰ359430 or \add вүҲtell the king what it meant\add*.
\v 9 Then KingВҰ359438 Belshatstsar became more afraid, his faceВҰ359442 \add вүҲwent whiter still\add*, and his noblesВҰ359445 \add also\add* \add вүҲhad no idea what to do\add*.
\p
\v 10 \add My now\add* the queen\f + \fr 5:10 \ft Possibly вҖҳthe previous queenвҖҷ, i.e., the queen mother (as the next verse displays her knowledge of past events).\f* had heard about what the king and his noblemenВҰ359452 had been saying, so she came into the banquetВҰ359454 houseВҰ359453 and said, вҖңLong live the king. Don't let \add вүҲthis get under your skin\add*. Don't let \add вүҲit drain you\add*.
\v 11 There'sВҰ359472 a man in your kingdomВҰ359474 who has the spiritВҰ359476 of the holy gods in him. In the daysВҰ359480 of your father, this man has illuminationВҰ359482 and insightВҰ359483 and wisdom like the wisdom of the gods. Your father KingВҰ359490 Nevukadnetstsar appointedВҰ359498 him chiefВҰ359493 of the magiciansВҰ359494, sorcerers, Chaldeans, and astrologersВҰ359497,
\v 12 becauseВҰ359504 this Daniel had an excellent spiritВҰ359506, knowledgeВҰ359509, and insightВҰ359510 for interpreting dreamsВҰ359512, explainingВҰ359513 riddlesВҰ359514, and solving problems. \add вүҲSo summonВҰ359529\add* Daniel who the kingВҰ359522 named Belteshatstsar and he'll tell \add >you\add* the interpretation.вҖқ
\rem /s1 Daniel Explains the Writing; The Writing on the Wall Interpreted
\p
\v 13 \add вүҲSo\add* Daniel was brought in to the king \add вүҲwho\add* said to \add *him\add*, вҖң\add So,\add* you're that DanielвҖ”one of the exilesВҰ359553 that my fatherВҰ359559 the king brought from YehudahВҰ359555.
\v 14 I'veВҰ359564 heard about youвҖ”\add вүЎheard\add* that the spiritВҰ359568 of the godsВҰ359569 is in you, and that \add вүҲyou have\add* illuminationВҰ359571 and insightВҰ359572 and excellent wisdomВҰ359573.
\v 15 Now the wise menВҰ359581 and enchantersВҰ359582 were broughtВҰ359579 in \add вүҲhere\add* to read this writingВҰ359585 \add on the wall\add* and \add вүҲtell\add* me itsВҰ359588 interpretation, butВҰ359578 they couldn't \add вүҲinterpret it\add*.
\v 16 ButВҰ359598 I'veВҰ359599 heardВҰ359599 aboutВҰ359600 youвҖ”that you're able to giveВҰ359608 interpretationsВҰ359607 and solveВҰ359610 problemsВҰ359609. Now, if you're able to read \add &that\add* writingВҰ359615 and \add вүҲtell me what it means\add*, you'll be clothedВҰ359620 withВҰ359631 \add вүҲkingly robes\add* and have a chainВҰ359621 of goldВҰ359626 \add placed\add* around your neck, and you'll be \add made\add* the third\add -highest\add* ruler inВҰ359631 the kingdomВҰ359631.вҖқ
\p
\v 17 вҖң\add вүҲI'm not after\add* your giftsВҰ359641, and your rewardsВҰ359644 \add вүҲcan be given to someoneВҰ359645 else,\add*вҖқ Daniel \add вүҲresponded\add*. вҖңButВҰ359638, I'll read the writingВҰ359648 to the king and \add вүЎI'll\add* \add вүҲtell you\add* the interpretationВҰ359651.
\p
\v 18 вҖңAs for you, \add вүҲyour majesty\add*, the highest godВҰ359657 gaveВҰ359664 the kingship, power, honourВҰ359662, and majesty, to your fatherВҰ359666 Nevukadnetstsar.
\v 19 Because of \add >that\add* power, all peoplesВҰ359676, nationsВҰ359677, and ethnic \add groups\add* trembledВҰ359680 and \add вүҲwere afraidВҰ359682 when hisВҰ359685 army approached\add*. He killed whoever he wanted, and he kept alive those he wanted. He \add вүҲpromoted\add* whoever he wanted, and he humiliated \add вүҲothers when he wanted to\add*.
\v 20 ButВҰ359711 when \add вүҲhe became proudВҰ359716 and stubborn\add* and started acting presumptuouslyВҰ359716, he was \add вүҲdisqualified\add* from the throneВҰ359720, and his \add вүҲsplendid reputation was deflated\add*.
\v 21 He was driven \add вүҲright out of the community\add*, and \add вүҲhe started behaving like\add* an animalВҰ359735вҖ”he \add ended up\add* livingВҰ359742 with wild donkeysВҰ359741 and eating grassВҰ359743 like a cow. \add He slept onВҰ359760 the ground, and inВҰ359760 the morning\add* his bodyВҰ359748 was wet with dew, untilВҰ359750 he \add finally\add* recognized that the highest godВҰ359757 is ruler over \add вүҲall\add* mankindВҰ359761 and that he \add вүҲappointsВҰ359766 whoever he wants as leaders over the kingdomsВҰ359760\add*.
\p
\v 22 вҖңYet you, Belshatstsar, his son, haven't humbled \add вүҲyourself despite already knowing all that\add*.
\v 23 \add On the contrary\add*, you'veВҰ359791 \add вүҲproudly promoted\add* yourselfВҰ359791 \add вүҲas being greater than\add* the masterВҰ359787 of the heavensВҰ359789. \add вүҲYou broughtВҰ359796 the temple cups inВҰ359808 here\add* and you and your noblesВҰ359801, your wivesВҰ359804 and your concubinesВҰ359805, have drunk wine from them. You praisedВҰ359826 the godsВҰ359809 \add вүҲmade from\add* silverВҰ359810 and goldВҰ359812, bronzeВҰ359813, iron, wood, and stoneВҰ359816, which can'tВҰ359818 see, or hearВҰ359823, or know \add >anything\add*, yet you haven't honoured the godВҰ359827 \add вүҲwho decides your future and every breathВҰ359830 that you take\add*.
\p
\v 24 вҖң\add So\add* then \add its\add* from his presenceВҰ359842 \add that\add* the palm of a handВҰ359848 was sentВҰ359843, and this \add вүҲmessage was written\add*.
\v 25 This \add вүҲis how itВҰ359856 reads\add*, вҖҳNumbered, numbered, weighed, andВҰ359860 divided,вҖҷ
\v 26 \add and\add* this is what itВҰ359871 means:
\li1 \bd Numbered\bd*: GodВҰ359869 has numberedВҰ359867 \add вүҲyourВҰ359870 days of leadership\add* and broughtВҰ359871 \add #them\add* to an endВҰ359871,
\li1
\v 27 \bd Weighed\bd*: You've been weighedВҰ359874 onВҰ359875 the scalesВҰ359875 and foundВҰ359876 deficient, \add and\add*
\li1
\v 28 \bd Divided\bd*: Your kingdomВҰ359881 has been divided and givenВҰ359882 to \add the\add* MedesВҰ359883 and \add the\add* Persians.вҖқ
\p
\v 29 Then Belshatstsar \add вүҲgave an order\add*, and they \add вүҲplaced a purpleВҰ359892 robe over Daniel's shoulders\add* and a goldВҰ359897 chainВҰ359893 was \add вүҲplaced\add* around his neck, and a proclamationВҰ359901 was made that he would \add now\add* be the third\add -highest\add* rulerВҰ359906 inВҰ359908 the kingdomВҰ359908.
\p
\v 30 \add However,\add* the Chaldean KingВҰ359914 Belshatstsar was killedВҰ359912 that \add вүҲvery\add* nightВҰ359911,
\v 31 and Dareyavesh \add (Darius)\add* the Mede \add вүҲbecame the new ruler at an age of\add* around sixty-two.
\c 6
\s1 Daniel gets fed to the lions
\rem /s1 Daniel in the Den of Lions; The Plot against Daniel; Daniel in the lion-pit; Daniel in the Lions' Den; Daniel in the Pit of Lions
\p
\v 1 \add The new King\add* DareyaveshВҰ359920 \add (DariusВҰ359920)\add* \add вүҲdecided to divide the kingdomВҰ359925 into 120 provinces with a governor over each one\add*.
\v 2 Over them were three higher officials (Daniel was one of them) that those governors were accountable to so that the king \add вүҲwouldn't be ripped off\add*,
\v 3 \add вүҲbutВҰ359949\add* because DanielВҰ359954 was exceptionally talented, he became noticed aboveВҰ359949 the \add other\add* high officials and governors, and the kingВҰ359966 \add вүҲdecided\add* to appoint him over the whole kingdom.
\v 4 \add вүҲThat led\add* the high officials and the governors to try to find \add вүҲsome fault with\add* Daniel with regard to \add вүҲhis administrativeВҰ359980 duties\add*. However, they weren't able to find any \add вүҲmisdemeanours or corruption that he could be accused of\add* becauseВҰ359984 he was \add ^honest, reliable, and diligent\add*.
\v 5 Then these men \add вүҲconcluded\add*, вҖңWe won'tВҰ360013 find any grounds for \add making an\add* accusation against this Daniel unless we find something against himВҰ360030 to do with the \add #laws\add* of his god.вҖқ
\p
\v 6 \add вүҲSo\add* those high officials and governors \add made a plan and\add* went as a group to the king and \add вүҲmade this suggestion\add*, вҖң\add вүҲLong live your majesty\add*, King Dareyavesh.
\v 7 All the high officials of the kingdom, the \add вүҲvarious leaders\add*, the counsellors, and the governors have consulted together that the king should establish and enforce a law that for thirty days, whoever makes a request of any god or \add вүЎof any\add* man other than you, \add вүҲyour majesty\add*, shall be thrown into the lions' den.
\v 8 Now, \add вүҲyour majesty\add*, sign the document and establishВҰ360079 \add вүҲthis law\add* so that it \add вүҲcan't then be revoked according to\add* the law of the Medes and Persians.вҖқ
\v 9 \add вүҲSo\add* KingВҰ360110 Dareyavesh signed the documentВҰ360114 and \add вүҲitВҰ360125 became law\add*.
\rem /s1 Daniel in the Lions' Den
\v 10 \add вүҲHowever although\add* Daniel knew that \add вүҲthat law had been passed\add*, he \add still\add* went into his house (with the windows in his \add вүҲupper room\add* open toward Yerushalem), and he continued to kneel three times a day to pray and give thanks to God, \add just\add* as he'd \add вүҲalways done\add*.
\p
\v 11 Then those \add вүҲofficials\add* wentВҰ360146 as a group and found Daniel \add вүҲprayingВҰ360163 to his godВҰ360166 and presenting him withВҰ360151 his requests\add*.
\v 12 Then they approached the king and \add вүҲreminded him about the law\add*, вҖңDidn't you \add вүҲintroduce a law\add* that within thirty days, any man who makes a petition to any godВҰ360190 or man, except to you, \add вүҲyour majesty\add*, must be thrown into the lions' den?вҖқ
\p вҖң\add вүҲYes, that's correct\add*,вҖқ answered the king. вҖңIt can't be revoked now according to the law of the Medes and Persians.вҖқ
\p
\v 13 Then they \add вүҲinformed\add* the king, вҖңDaniel who was exiled from Yehudah, pays no attention to you, \add вүҲyour majesty\add*, or to the \add вүҲlaw thatВҰ360238 you introduced\add*, because he petitions \add his godВҰ360217\add* three times a day.вҖқ
\p
\v 14 When the king heard \add вүҲthat\add*, was very upset and \add вүҲfor that entire dayВҰ360272, he actively tried to think of a way to get Daniel out of it\add*.
\v 15 \add вүҲHowever, the group of men returned\add* to the king and said, вҖңYou know, \add вүҲyour majesty\add*, that it's a law of the Medes and Persians, that no rule or law that the king establishes can be changed.вҖқ
\p
\v 16 \add вүҲSo\add* the king gave an order, and Daniel was brought in and the king respondedВҰ360305 and told \add *him\add*, вҖңMay your god, who you serve continually, save you.вҖқ Then Daniel was thrown \add down\add* into the lions' den.
\v 17 A stone was broughtВҰ360331 and laid over the opening of the den, and the king sealed it with his own signet ring and with the signet rings of his nobles so that \add вүҲno one could sneak Daniel out\add*.
\v 18 Then the kingВҰ360362 went to his palace and spent the night \add вүҲwithout eating\add*. \add вүҲHe refused all\add* entertainment, and \add вүҲhe couldn't sleep\add*.
\s2 Daniel's saved from the lions
\rem /s1 Daniel Saved from the Lions
\p
\v 19 ThenВҰ360376 the kingВҰ360376 got up at dawn, and \add вүҲhurried out\add* to the lions' den.
\v 20 As he \add вүҲapproached\add* the den, he called out inВҰ360392 a worried voice, вҖңDaniel, Daniel, servant of the living god. Has your god, who you serve continually, been able to save you from the lionsВҰ360399?вҖқ
\p
\v 21 вҖң\add вүҲLong live\add* the kingВҰ360410,вҖқ Daniel \add вүҲcalled back\add*.
\v 22 вҖңMy god sent his angel and shut the lions' mouths, and they haven't hurt me, because \add вүҲhe saw that I wasn't guilty of anything\add*. Also, \add вүҲyour majesty\add*, I haven't \add вүҲwronged you in any way\add*.вҖқ
\p
\v 23 Then the kingВҰ360462 was very happy, and ordered that Daniel be pulled up out of the den. So Daniel was lifted out of the den, and \add вүҲhe didn'tВҰ360449 even have a scratch\add* on him, becauseВҰ360453 he had trusted in his godВҰ360443.
\v 24 \add Then\add* the kingВҰ360469 \add вүҲordered the arrest of\add* the men who had maliciously accused Daniel, and \add вүҲhad them and their wives and children thrown\add* into the lions' denвҖ”they didn'tВҰ360487 \add even\add* reach the bottom of the den before the lions overpowered them and \add вүҲtore them to pieces\add*.
\p
\v 25 Then KingВҰ360497 Dareyavesh \add (Darius)\add* wrote to all the peoples, nations, and \add вүҲethnic groups right across hisВҰ360504 kingdom\add*: вҖңMay you all \add вүҲbe enjoying peace and prosperity\add*.
\v 26 I decree thatВҰ360539 \add вүҲeveryone throughout\add* my kingdom is to \add вүҲobey and respect\add* Daniel's god, because he is the \add вүҲeternal\add*, livingВҰ360541 God. His kingdom \add вүҲwill never\add* be destroyed, and his \add вүҲrule will continue forever\add*.
\v 27 He delivers and rescues, and he does \add вүҲall kinds of miracles\add* in the heavens and on earth. He's rescued Daniel from the \add вүҲstrength and power\add* of the lions.вҖқ
\p
\v 28 \add вүҲSo\add* Daniel prospered during the reign of Dareyavesh and during the reign of Koresh \add (Cyrus)\add* the Persian.
\c 7
\s1 Daniel's vision of four creatures
\rem /s1 Daniel's Vision of Four Beasts; Daniel's Vision of the Four Beasts; Visions of the Four Beasts; Daniel's visions; Daniel's Dream of Four Beasts
\p
\v 1 \add Previously,\add* in Babylonian KingВҰ360621 Belshatstsar's first year, Daniel had seen a dream and visionsВҰ360626 in his mind while lying on his bed. Then he wroteВҰ360633 the dream down and \add вүҲgave a summary of it\add*.
\v 2 \add *He\add* \add вүҲexplained\add*:
\p In my visionВҰ360643 atВҰ360643 nightВҰ360646 I was looking, and \add вүҲsuddenly\add*, the fourВҰ360648 windsВҰ360649 were stirringВҰ360651 up the massive ocean,
\v 3 andВҰ360655 fourВҰ360655 hugeВҰ360657 creatures, each one differentВҰ360662 from the other, were comingВҰ360658 up out of \add *it\add*.\x + \xo 7:3: \xt Rev 13:1; 17:8.\x*
\li1
\v 4 The firstВҰ360668 \add one\add* was like a lionВҰ360669 butВҰ360670 had the wings of an eagleВҰ360673. \add вүҲButВҰ360670 as I watched, its wings were torn\add* off, and it was liftedВҰ360682 \add вүҲup\add* and made to standВҰ360690 on two feetВҰ360688 like a man, and then it was givenВҰ360693 a \add вүҲhumanВҰ360692\add* mindВҰ360691.\x + \xo 7:4-6: \xt Rev 13:2.\x*
\li1
\v 5 The secondВҰ360699 creature resembled a bear \add вүҲwithВҰ360708 one arm raisedВҰ360705\add*. \add вүҲIt was chomping on\add* threeВҰ360706 ribs and it was told to go and \add вүҲgorge itself\add* on \add more\add* meatВҰ360717.
\li1
\v 6 \add вүҲNext I saw anotherВҰ360725 creature that resembled\add* a leopardВҰ360726, \add вүҲbutВҰ360724\add* with four wings \add вүҲ(like birds' wings) attached to\add* its back, and with four headsВҰ360738. \add вүҲIt was givenВҰ360741 the authority to rule people\add*.
\li1
\v 7 The final creature that I saw inВҰ360748 the visionВҰ360748 was dreadfulВҰ360755 and terrifyingВҰ360754. It was extremely strongВҰ360756 withВҰ360748 large iron teethВҰ360758 and it was devouringВҰ360764 \add >things\add* then tramplingВҰ360769 and crushingВҰ360765 the remainderВҰ360766. \add вүҲAnother differenceВҰ360771 from the other creatures was that it had tenВҰ360780 hornsВҰ360779 onВҰ360748 its head\add*.\x + \xo 7:7: \xt Rev 12:3; 13:1; 17:3.\x*
\p
\v 8 While I was considering the horns, \add вүҲsuddenly\add* anotherВҰ360788 horn, a little one, came up amongВҰ360791 \add вүҲthe others\add* and threeВҰ360793 of the firstВҰ360797 horns \add вүҲthat were inВҰ360785 its way got pulled completely out\add*. \add вүҲIncredibly\add*, this \add new\add* had eyes like a person and a mouthВҰ360811 \add вүҲthat had a lot of incredible things to say\add*.\x + \xo 7:8,11: \xt Rev 13:5.\x*
\rem /s1 The revelation of God concerning the one not die
\rem /s1 Judgment before the Ancient One; The Vision of the One Who Has Been Living Forever
\q1
\v 9 I kept looking \add in the vision\add* while thrones were set up and the ancientВҰ360821 \add вүҲone\add* took his seat. His clothingВҰ360824 was as whiteВҰ360827 as snow, and his hair \add looked\add* like pure wool. His throne was \add вүҲflaming with\add* fire, \add and\add* its wheelsВҰ360837 were burningВҰ360839 fire.\x + \xo 7:9: a \xt Rev 20:4; \xo b \xt Rev 1:14.\x*
\v 10 A riverВҰ360841 of fireВҰ360844 was comingВҰ360846 out and flowingВҰ360845 \add вүҲalong in front of\add* him. Thousands upon thousandsВҰ360851 servedВҰ360853 him, and myriads upon myriads were standingВҰ360858 \add вүҲin front of\add* him. The courtВҰ360859 satВҰ360860 \add in session\add* and the documents were openedВҰ360862.\x + \xo 7:10: a \xt Rev 5:11; \xo b \xt Rev 20:12.\x*
\p
\v 11 Then I continued looking because of the \add вүҲamazing things\add* that the horn was saying. I kept looking untilВҰ360877 that \add final\add* creature was killedВҰ360879 and itsВҰ360882 bodyВҰ360882 destroyedВҰ360881 \add вүҲin\add* the fireВҰ360885.
\v 12 As for the other creatures, theirВҰ360890 \add вүҲauthority to rule\add* was taken away, butВҰ360887 an extensionВҰ360891 of lifeВҰ360892 was givenВҰ360893 to them for a season andВҰ360887 a time.
\p
\v 13 IВҰ360901 was looking inВҰ360902 the visionsВҰ360902 of the nightВҰ360903, and \add вүҲsuddenly\add*, \add вүҲsomeone like a human male\add* was comingВҰ360911 withВҰ360902 the cloudsВҰ360907, and he came to the ancientВҰ360915 \add вүҲone\add* and was presentedВҰ360919 to him.\x + \xo 7:13: \xt Mat 24:30; 26:64; Mrk 13:26; 14:62; Luk 21:27; Rev 1:7,13; 14:14.\x*
\v 14 He was givenВҰ360922 \add вүҲauthority to rule\add* and \add вүҲsplendour\add* and a kingdom, so thatВҰ360935 all the peoplesВҰ360927, nationsВҰ360928, and \add вүҲethnic groups\add* will serve him. His \add вүҲauthority will never end\add*, and his kingdom \add вүҲwill never\add* be destroyedВҰ360943.\x + \xo 7:14: \xt Rev 11:15.\x*
\s1 The meaning of the visions
\rem /s1 Daniel's Visions Interpreted; The Interpretation of the Dream; The Visions Are Explained; The Vision Is Explained
\p
\v 15 As for me, Daniel, my spirit was distressedВҰ360946 insideВҰ360950 me, andВҰ360952 the visionsВҰ360952 inВҰ360950 my \add вүҲmind\add* kept alarmingВҰ360954 me.
\v 16 I approachedВҰ360956 one of those who were standingВҰ360962 there and asked himВҰ360966 \add вүҲwhat was going on\add*, so he told me, and then he revealed the interpretationВҰ360975 of those thingsВҰ360976 to me:
\mi
\v 17 Those four large creatures, they represent four \add вүҲkingdoms\add* thatВҰ360982 will \add вүҲcome to be in the world\add*,
\v 18 \add вүҲbutВҰ360992\add* the \add вүҲdedicated followers\add* of the highest one will receiveВҰ360992 the kingdom, andВҰ360992 they will \add вүҲtake possessionВҰ360996 of\add* the kingdom foreverВҰ361003.
\p
\v 19 \add вүҲButВҰ361027 IВҰ361006 still wanted to knowВҰ361007 more\add* about the fourthВҰ361011 creature thatВҰ361012 was differentВҰ361015 from all the others, absolutely dreadful, with its iron teethВҰ361022 and bronzeВҰ361030 clawsВҰ361027, and whichВҰ361012 devouredВҰ361031, then crushed and trampledВҰ361036 down with its feetВҰ361034 what was left.
\v 20 \add вүЎI also wanted to know\add* aboutВҰ361038 the tenВҰ361041 horns onВҰ361043 its headВҰ361043, and the other horn that cameВҰ361046 up later, withВҰ361043 threeВҰ361053 \add other\add* horns falling. That horn had eyesВҰ361056 and a mouthВҰ361058 that said amazing things, and itВҰ361046 looked \add вүҲstronger\add* than the others.
\v 21 IВҰ361068 kept watching, and that horn was waging war with those followers and \add вүҲgaining over\add* them\x + \xo 7:21: \xt Rev 13:7.\x*
\v 22 until the ancientВҰ361083 \add one\add* arrived and \add вүҲjudgedВҰ361085 in favourВҰ361087 of his followers\add*. Then the timeВҰ361089 arrived when \add *they\add* tookВҰ361092 possessionВҰ361092 of the kingdomВҰ361091.\x + \xo 7:22: \xt Rev 20:4.\x*
\p
\v 23 Then he saidВҰ361096:
\mi The fourth creature will be a fourth kingdomВҰ361099 inВҰ361103 the world whichВҰ361104 will be differentВҰ361105 from all the \add other\add* kingdomsВҰ361110. It will devourВҰ361111 the whole world, and trampleВҰ361115 it down and crushВҰ361116 it.
\v 24 As for the ten hornsВҰ361118, ten kings will \add вүҲbecome prominent\add* in that kingdomВҰ361121, and thenВҰ361118 anotherВҰ361125 \add вүЎking\add* will appear. He will be differentВҰ361129 from the previous \add вүЎkings\add*, and he will \add вүҲovercome\add* threeВҰ361133 \add *of them\add*. \x + \xo 7:24: \xt Rev 17:12.\x*
\v 25 He will speakВҰ361141 \add вүҲout\add* againstВҰ361138 the highest one and will wear out the highest one's \add вүҲfollowers\add*. He will intend to changeВҰ361146 the times and the law, and \add indeed\add* \add вүҲhe'll be allowed to\add* for a two times and a half.\x + \xo 7:25: \xt Rev 12:14; 13:5-6.\x*
\v 26 ButВҰ361158 the courtВҰ361158 will sitВҰ361159, and thenВҰ361158 his \add вүҲauthority to rule\add* will be taken awayвҖ”to \add вүҲperish and be forever destroyedВҰ361163\add*.
\v 27 ThenВҰ361168 the kingdom and the \add вүҲauthority to rule\add* and the greatnessВҰ361170 of the kingdomsВҰ361172 underВҰ361173 all the heavensВҰ361176 will be givenВҰ361177 to the peopleВҰ361178 \add вүҲwho are the followers\add* of the highest one. His kingdom will \add вүҲcontinue forever\add*, and all \add вүҲearthly rulers\add* will serve and obey him.\x + \xo 7:27: a \xt Rev 20:4; \xo b \xt Rev 22:5.\x*
\p
\v 28 \add вүҲThat's everything that I saw\add* \add inВҰ361207 my visions\add*. As for me, Daniel, my thoughtsВҰ361201 \add вүҲmade me very upset\add* and my faceВҰ361203 turned pale, \add вүҲbutВҰ361203\add* I keptВҰ361208 the matter \add вүҲto myself\add*.
\c 8
\s1 Daniel's sheep and goat vision
\rem /s1 Daniel's Vision of a Ram and Goat; Daniel's Vision of a Ram and a Goat; Vision of a Ram and a Goat
\p
\v 1 In the third yearВҰ361211 of KingВҰ361215 Belshatstsar's reignВҰ361213, I, Daniel, had \add вүҲanother\add* visionВҰ361216вҖ”\add different from\add* the previous one.
\v 2 In the vision, I saw thatВҰ361233 I was atВҰ361227 the fortress in Shusan (\add often called SusaВҰ361231,\add* in Eylam provinceВҰ361235), beside the UlaiВҰ361243 Canal.
\v 3 ThenВҰ361245 I \add вүҲlooked up\add*, and \add вүҲto my surprise, there was\add* a ram standingВҰ361252 beside the canalВҰ361254. It had twoВҰ361256 horns and bothВҰ361256 horns were long, butВҰ361245 one was longer than the other, and the longer one \add вүҲhad grown\add* last.
\v 4 I sawВҰ361268 the ram charging westwardВҰ361273, and northwardВҰ361274, and southwardВҰ361275вҖ”no animal could stand \add вүҲagainstВҰ361282 it\add*вҖ”thereВҰ361283 was no one to rescue \add вүҲanything from it\add*. \add *The ram\add* did \add вүҲwhatever it wanted, and it becameВҰ361288 very powerfulВҰ361285\add*.
\p
\v 5 As I was observingВҰ361293, suddenly a billy goat was comingВҰ361298 from the west, \add вүҲcrossing the entireВҰ361305 world\add* withoutВҰ361308 touchingВҰ361309 the ground. The goat had a prominent horn betweenВҰ361314 its eyesВҰ361315.
\v 6 In a powerful rageВҰ361330, it charged atВҰ361330 the two-horned ram thatВҰ361323 I had seenВҰ361324 standingВҰ361325 inВҰ361330 frontВҰ361326 of the canalВҰ361327.
\v 7 I sawВҰ361333 \add @the furious goat\add* \add вүҲreach\add* the ram and strike it, shattering \add @the ram's\add* twoВҰ361347 hornsВҰ361348. The ram \add вүҲwasn't strong enough to stay standingВҰ361354 so\add* it was knocked to the ground and trampledВҰ361358 onВҰ361353вҖ”there was no one who could rescue the ram from \add @the goat's\add* powerВҰ361364.
\p
\v 8 ThenВҰ361366 the billy goat \add вүҲbecameВҰ361372 even more powerfulВҰ361372, butВҰ361366 at its peak\add*, the largeВҰ361375 horn was brokenВҰ361373, andВҰ361366 in its placeВҰ361379, four prominent horns came up \add вүҲfacing in the four different compass directions\add*.
\v 9 ThenВҰ361384 a smallВҰ361392 horn grew out of one of themвҖ”itВҰ361388 grew very long towards the southВҰ361398, towards the east, andВҰ361384 towards the beautifulВҰ361404 land \add of Yisrael\add*.
